metadata.abstract: The study examines the ordinary repertory of Aquileia and Cividale, highlighting the German-Central European orientation of these sources, which contrasts with other Italian regions. Through comparative analysis, the research identifies unique melodies and trends, emphasizing the intercultural influences and the need for cautious interpretation due to limitations in available data. The findings suggest a distinct character for the Aquileian sources, influenced by historical and geographical factors, and propose further examination of the repertory's chronology and context to enhance understanding.

For this reason I undertake now to give an overall picture of a special repertory, the ordinary repertory, in a special source group, the sources from Aquileia and Cividale. Aiming at fitting the conference theme, I do this despite that in the collection of the information I was compelled to accept compromises. Since few sources were available on microfilm, I decided to supplement my data bank with information gathered from the published ordinary catalogues. Since it is well known that these are by no means correct in every respect, my collected information and the conclusion based on it must be considered cautiously. It is also known that these catalogues are not suitable for the examination of several aspects. Thus, I have already explained the importance of these catalogues and the importance of the analysis of them. I have only drawn conclusions beyond the occurrence and or absence of certain melodies, only where these seem to be sufficiently convincing. Though experimental in nature, the following overview supplements usefully and harmonizes well with our knowledge about the consuetudo Aquileiensis. For a survey of the ordinary repertory of Aquileia, I used a coherent source group which can be seen in your handout. Example 1. After cataloguing all ordinary melodies in them, I analyzed what kind of melodies the repertories are compiled from and how they can be grouped, which melodies are Einzelmelodien, if there are any examples at all, and which appear more frequently in the sources. The latter requires further differentiation, for it is by no means indifferent what brought the repertory to the original code behind the individual melodies belonging to this group. The appearance of the general European repertory calls for an explanation less than that of regional or local melodies do. Finally, it is necessary to check whether observations concerning the dissemination of melodies indicate some trends, or whether it is possible to grasp the character of the source group under discussion on the basis of them, at least in this repertory. Formulated in another way, is any kind of orientation palpable in the analyzed source group? Now, let's take a look at concrete observations in the order of the dissemination of melodies. The comparative tables in example 2 show the content of the source group. In this case, I have placed the sources according to genre. On the basis of this information, I have prepared a table with a grouping of melodies. In example 3, I placed melodies that are documented in the catalogues from one source alone. The sanctus melody 189 is an exception since it occurs in three sources, but all from Cividale. Although, as concrete examples, we can regard this Einzelmelodien as characteristic of the area or source group under discussion, their number doesn't differ from the average of such melodies in other areas. For example, concerning Italy, Schildbach registers 26 such melodies from the 11th up to the 18th century. In the comparative tables, I have marked the Einzelmelodien together with the melodies known only from Italian sources as underlined, as you can see in example 2.

In the second group of example 3, I have collected melodies that were used all over Europe through the centuries and which, according to my information, became integral elements of the Aquileian tradition as well. Those well-known melodies that occur only exceptionally in Aquileia are placed in the next row of this table.

The original melodies are undoubtedly more interesting than those of the above-mentioned groups. The next two categories were not arbitrarily created but took shape almost automatically on the basis of collected information on the distribution of the melodies. In the sources of Aquileia we find a remarkably great number of melodies that were disseminated mainly in German and Central European manuscripts. In the comparative tables these are indicated in bold lettering. This observation seems to be of even greater importance by the fact that besides the German and Ostlandish sources using the term of the catalogues they occur mostly or exclusively in Aquileia and codices.
So, not in other Italian manuscripts. On the basis of their dissemination in Italian sources the items of this group can be differentiated further as can be seen in example 4.

Among these German-oriented melodies, we find only one that proves to be widely disseminated in Italian regions. Beyond numerous north Italian sources, this Kyrian number 151 occurs in Beneventan manuscripts as well. It is striking that beside the overall similarity in their orientation, the sources from Aquileia and Cividale do not agree with each other in every respect. For example, while the Gloria number 48 occurs only in sources from Cividale, the Kyrian melodies number 144 or number 74 can be exclusively documented from Aquileia.

The observations in the ordinary repertory, which will be summarized later on, agree with this formulation.

Perhaps the most notable observation is that the German Ostländisch or Ostfrankisch, I would say, orientation reveals itself on a more general level than that of the inner differentiation of the diocese. Such melodies prevail not only in the common stock of melodies, but among the local ones too. So, the melodies were in use either only in Aquileia or only in Cividale. Formulated in another way, the source groups of Aquileia, in the narrow sense, and Cividale reveal a German-Central European orientation also independently of each other. It is frequently emphasized in the literature that besides indications of a connection between Aquileia and the neighboring Italias, the influence of the northern areas can be strongly felt. This may be attributed to several factors, the listing of which would exceed the limits of this paper. Suffice it to mention the intercultural position of this area, the fact that between the 11th and 13th centuries all patriarchs were of German origin, or the influence of the Italian monasteries founded from here-so, etc. The many experiences referring to this, served as a basis for the view that research should concentrate on an identification of evidence of this German influence, rather than the definition of an independent and, to a certain extent, imaginary Aquileian liturgy. In any case, an examination of the ordinary repertory of Aquileia coincides with these observations.

A comparative analysis of the Cividale repertory, of the sources, raises another critical question. After the rough designation system used by Melnicki and Bosse for the sources, Schildbach introduced further differentiation by which he wished to reflect the intercultural character of some sources. He applied to only two sources, the Berlin source and the Udine mentioned above, the designation JD. Italienisch, Deutsch, Friaulich. Schildbach extended it over one more source as well. This is a source from Venetia.

Of course, in the arbitrariness, or one might say haphazardness in the selection of sources, a certain danger is concealed. Nevertheless, on the basis of a relatively large number of instances, the characteristic points reveal themselves and confirm the relative independence of the Aquileian source group. Some of these characteristic points connect to a wide circle of Italian sources to each other, while others serve as a basis for further differentiation.
